7. Conclusion

The post attempts to neutralize a longstanding cultural observation about quantum mechanics by reframing it as a citation dispute and a semantic misunderstanding.

It succeeds only in demonstrating that:
	•	Mathematical operational competence does not settle interpretational ambiguity.
	•	Humor does not nullify epistemic tension.
	•	Attribution debates do not resolve foundational problems.
	•	“Understanding” cannot be reduced to computational literacy.

Therefore, the assertion that “we understand quantum mechanics just fine” is simultaneously defensible, incomplete, and deeply misleading.

In summary:

Quantum mechanics is either fully understood, partially understood, or not understood at all—depending entirely on which definition one quietly substitutes into the word “understanding,” which, fortunately, has now been conclusively resolved as unproblematic.

The Institute considers the matter closed pending further confusion.

